article.description: Cheryl Ford had 21 points and nine rebounds, and Deanna Nolan scored 18 points to lead the defending WNBA champion Detroit Shock past the New York Liberty 76-66 Sunday, evening their first-round WNBA playoff series at 1-1.
article.headline: Ford's 21 points lead Detroit to playoff win
article.linkText: Driving Ford: Shock pull even with Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Cheryl Ford had 21 points and nine rebounds, and
Deanna Nolan scored 18 points to lead the defending WNBA champion
Detroit Shock past the New York Liberty 76-66 Sunday, evening their
first-round WNBA playoff series at 1-1.

Ruth Riley had 13 points and Barbara Farris added 11 points and
nine rebounds for Detroit, which bounced back after losing the
opening game of the best-of-three series at home Friday night.

Reserve center La'Keshia Frett led the Liberty with a
career-high 20 points, and Crystal Robinson added 15. New York lost
for just the second time in its last seven games overall, and
second time in the last nine at home.

After New York took its first lead of the game at 33-32 on
Bethany Donaphin's layup 46 seconds into the second half, Detroit
went on a 16-2 run over the next four minutes to take a 13-point
lead. The Shock stretched their lead to 17 midway through the
period.

The Liberty cut the deficit to 62-55 on Shameka Christon's
3-pointer with 5:13 remaining in the game.

Detroit followed with an 8-2 run to push its lead back up to
13, and New York didn't get closer than nine the rest of the way.

The Liberty set a franchise playoff record with 10 3-pointers,
though they attempted 29. New York matched its previous high of
nine in its Game 1 victory Friday night at Detroit.

The Shock made 27 of 33 free throws, compared to 6-of-8 for the
Liberty.

Ford set a playoff high for scoring while shooting 7-for-15 from
the field and 7-for-8 on free throws.

The Shock, playing without leading-scorer Swin Cash since she
tore knee ligaments on Sept. 11, used a bigger lineup in an attempt
to force the Liberty to try to win again with their outside
shooting. The 6-foot-3 Barbara Farris started at forward in place
of Merlakia Jones, who had been starting since Cash's injury.

The move paid off as Detroit's starting frontcourt combined for
44 points and 24 rebounds, compared to 18 points and 14 boards for
its Liberty counterpart. The Shock also outscored the Liberty in
the paint 30-20.

The Shock led by as many 12 points in the first half before the
Liberty chipped away and outscored Detroit 16-6 over the final 10
minutes of the period. Robinson capped New York's flurry with a
pair of 3-pointers by Robinson in the last 33 seconds.

The deciding Game 3 is Tuesday at Madison Square Garden.
